			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=3960')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=48232&amp;TOPIC_ID=5882&amp;FORUM_ID=13&amp;CAT_ID=2&amp;Forum_Title=Newbie+Land&amp;Topic_Title=Newbie+needs+help+to+choose+race&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         When I bought the game I had done enough research to know I wanted a necro, but I created a woodelf druid to learn the game mechanics and dynamics. There's an awful lot of learning curve to overcome and I figured an "easy" character would get me up to speed in the least amount of time. This worked out really well for me, but some people will have no problem starting with harder classes, so do what's best for you.</P><P>I picked Gnome to be different - there aren't very many gnome necros on Vazaelle. I figured stats differences could be fixed with gear - at level 31 I've got 173 INT so I think I'm doing pretty well. The Iksar regen factor was appealing but, in the end, I decided it wasn't worth the 20% exp penalty and extra KOS hassles. (This was back when pets would take exp.) I made an Iksar monk later to satisfy my lizardly curiosity.</P><P>The newbie areas for gnomes in Steamfont have been improved recently, so it's much easier to level up than when I started. The new newbie armor quests also seem to be pretty good.</P><P>Smyrt Bertoxxnik<BR>31 Gnome Necromancer<BR>Vazaelle<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

